It was no surprise that the Momentum activists in my local party wanted to subject me to censorship.
After all, I am the last in the line of Labour MPs to date to be told that he is not desirable - that is all, because we are not hiding our opinion.
My parliamentary colleague, Joan Ryan, was treated in a similar way because she was resolute in her opposition to anti-Semitism.
In my case, the movement for censorship criticised me for not agreeing with Jeremy Corbyn.
For the importance of economically responsible politics, for national security, for Europe — ironically, but these were issues on which Jeremy disagreed with previous leaders.
A statement on the Labour meeting in East Nottingham on Friday said that 'we want the meetings to be inclusive and productive'.
Most of the meetings that took place during the career of my eight local Labour MPs were exactly that.
Unfortunately, the atmosphere of many meetings today is different and the promises of a "kinder, more gentle" policy have long been forgotten, if ever there were any.
It has become increasingly clear that the Labour Party does not want to tolerate different views, and any view is judged on whether it is acceptable to the party leadership.
It started shortly after Jeremy took the lead: colleagues who I think share our political views began to expect me to turn 180 degrees and accept opinions that I would never have accepted otherwise, whether it was for national security or a single EU market.
When I speak in public – and it doesn’t matter what I’m saying – there’s a tirade about using social media to call for a ban on running in the next election, denouncing the center’s policies, claiming that I don’t have a place in the Labour Party.
And it's not just my experience.
Indeed, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments made against me are usually political.
I admire the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who are confronted every day with a stream of sexist and racist insults, but never shy away.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this political era is how normal exploitation has become.
Jeremy Corbyn announced last week that the Labour Party must cultivate a culture of tolerance.
In reality, we are no longer an organisation that is prepared for a multiplicity of views, and with every expression of distrust or change in selection rules, the party is shrinking.
Over the past two years, I have often been advised not to jump on harrows, think about what I am talking about, and then "everything will be fine" with me.
But that's not why I decided to get involved in politics.
Ever since I joined Labour 32 years ago as a student in response to the negligence of the Thatcher government, which literally led my integrated school class to collapse, I have set myself the task of fighting for better public services for those most in need, both as a local councillor and as a government minister.
I have never concealed my political views, not even in the previous elections.
No one in the East of Nottingham had any reason to doubt my position on political issues and in areas where I disagreed with the existing government.
To those who pushed forward the proposal on Friday, I can only say that, at a time when the country is moving decisively towards Brexit, which will harm households, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the Labour Party leader.
But basically, the only thing I want to say is not to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether or not they are Labour: I am proud to serve you, and I promise you that no threats of exclusion or reminders that no one is irreplaceable in politics will stop me from doing what I think is best for all of you.
Chris Leslie is a Member of Parliament from East Nottingham
