John Edwards: Language skills are vital for global citizens
The Scottish Independent Schools have a reputation for outstanding educational institutions and have maintained this reputation in 2018, when once again outstanding exam results were obtained, which are further enhanced by individual and collective achievements in sports, arts, music and other community events.
These schools, with a total of 30,000 pupils in Scotland and represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level for their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools have set themselves the goal of preparing their students for further and higher education, for their chosen careers and for their lives as citizens of the world.
As an education sector that can design and implement specific school programmes, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable subject in our schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a person in a language he understands, it stays in his consciousness.
If you speak his mother tongue, it stays in his heart."
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot simply rely on English when we want to build relationships and gain the trust of people from other countries.
With the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the largest number of exams passed in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who taught foreign languages achieved the highest score of A.
According to the Scottish Council of Independent Schools, in 74 schools, 72 percent of the students received the highest grade of A in Chinese, and 72 percent of those who learned German, 69 percent of those who learned French, and 63 percent of those who learned Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language as an optional subject is now as highly valued in the independent school curriculum as in the science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) group.
A 2014 survey by the British Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17 percent of employers cited a lack of language skills as a reason for not being able to fill vacancies.
As a result, language skills are increasingly becoming a must in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With the increase in job opportunities that will require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of their chosen career, learning a foreign language will give them the real advantage of such a long-term skill in the future.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically improve the competitiveness of a multilingual speaker.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent did not speak a foreign language well enough to keep a conversation going, while French was the only language spoken by a double-digit number, 15 percent.
That is why investing in language teaching is important for today's children.
Multilingualism, especially in developing countries, will give children a better chance of meaningful work.
Schools in Scotland differ in the languages they teach.
Some schools will pay more attention to the most common modern languages, while others will teach languages such as Chinese and Japanese, which are considered the most important for Britain’s future, according to plans for 2020.
Whatever your child’s interests may be, independent schools will always have a choice of several languages, and teachers will be experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a language environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may be.
Currently, in the global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still vitally important for the future of the country, so this fact must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered as "skills for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish young people this choice, diversity and excellence.
Il faut bien le faire (It must be done).
John Edwards is Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council.
