North Korea says it will “never” disarm unilaterally without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions had deepened its mistrust of the United States, and North Korea would under no circumstances unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons in such a situation.
Ri Yong Ho informed the organization’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant steps of goodwill” over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and vowing never to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“However, we do not see an adequate response from the United States,” he said.
“If there is no trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our country’s security, and under these circumstances, we will never unilaterally disarm first.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known accusations of Washington’s opposition to a “gradual” approach to denuclearization, according to which Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual steps, his statement left an impression because it did not automatically reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang had done before.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at a meeting in Singapore on June 12 between the first US president and the North Korean leader, when Kim promised to work for the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" and Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has attempted to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has stated that Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that ‘denuclearization must come first,’ and raises the level of pressure from sanctions to achieve the goal by force, even opposing the ‘declaration of the end of the war’,” Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions could put us on our knees is an empty fantasy, cherished by people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions only deepens our mistrust."
Ri was not talking about the intentions regarding the second time Kim met Trump, which the US leader had specifically mentioned in a speech to the United Nations this week.
In his speech, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If South Korea were on the other side of the issue of denuclearisation rather than the United States, the denuclearisation of the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a deadlock."
However, Ri's tone was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korea would target the US mainland after "Evil President Trump" called Kim a "missile" on a suicide mission.
This year, at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking steps toward disarmament, but stressed that more needs to be done and that sanctions must be maintained until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had not scheduled a specific time, stressing that “it doesn’t matter whether it takes two years, three years or five months.”
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its efforts.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that "the implementation of Security Council sanctions must be vigorously pursued, without mistakes, until a final and credible denuclearization has been achieved."
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions since 2006 in an attempt to reduce funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic weapons programmes.
Pompeo met Ri outside the meetings of the UN General Assembly, and was then informed that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second meeting.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but the last trip was not successful.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress had been made, but hours later North Korea accused him of "gangster-worthy demands".
During a meeting with Moon earlier this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle the weapons range and the nuclear complex if the United States takes "appropriate measures".
According to him, Kim had informed him that the "appropriate measures" North Korea wants to see are the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and steps towards normalizing relations with Washington.
